class Solution {
public:
    int minStartingIndex(string s, string pattern) {
        int n = s.size(), m = pattern.size();
        for (int i = 0; i <= n - m; i++) {
            int diff = 0;
            for (int j = 0; j < m; j++) {
                if (s[i + j] != pattern[j]) diff++;
            }
            if (diff == 1) return i;
        }
        return -1;
    }
};
```

efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(n*m)
space complexity: O(1)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: This solution iterates over the string s and checks each substring of length m (the length of the pattern) to see if it's almost equal to the pattern. It uses two nested loops to compare the characters of the substring and the pattern, and keeps track of the number of differences. If the number of differences is 1, it returns the starting index of the substring. If no such index is found after checking all substrings, it returns -1. This solution has a high efficiency because it only needs to iterate over the string once and uses a constant amount of space.

